The shape of the redwine dataframe is (1599, 12) and the shape of the whitewine dataframe is (4898, 12), meaning that for both, we have 12 columns, corresponding to the 11 different features (we can read them above) and the last column for the label (quality). There are respectively 1599 and 4898 different entries.

1.2. Data cleaning¶

1.3. Data visualisation¶

For the next cells, we'll plot the distribution of each column according to each 'quality'. In other words, we will try to check how a given feature influences the wine quality. Also, we'll do it independently for both datasets to check if there is any difference in trends.

In [6]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (30,30))
for i in range(11):
    plt.subplot(4,3,i+1)
    sns.barplot(x = 'quality', y = redwine.columns[i], data = redwine, palette='muted')
    plt.title('Distribution of '+redwine.columns[i]+' according to quality')
fig.suptitle('Red wine: Distribution of each feature wr to quality', y=0.92, fontsize=30)
plt.show()
Comments¶

The histograms above allow us to extract various trends and information about each feature for the redwine dataset.

First there are some features that seem to be more or less similar or independent of quality. These features will not allow us to give any specification to classify the wine's quality. Fixed acidity, residual sugar, density, or pH. Also, free and total sulfur dioxide are low for good and bad wines and high for middle quality wines.

On the other hand, there are some features that seem to have a linear influence on the quality and will allow us to classify the wines by quality easily.

  • Volatile acidity goes down with quality
  • Citric acid goes up with quality
  • Chlorides goes down with quality
  • Sulphates goes up with quality
  • Alcohol goes up with quality

Comments¶

The histograms above allow us to extract various trends and information about each feature for the whitewine dataset.

The trends are very much similar compared to the other dataset except for some slight differences. Volatile and citric acidity do no have the same smooth trends.

Now, we'll apply a RFECV method (Recursive Feature Elimination) using Random Forest Classifier as a model, in order to determine which are the most important features, and if they are similar for both datasets.

In [37]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFECV
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import log_loss

rfc = RandomForestClassifier()
rfecv = RFECV(estimator=rfc, step=1, cv=StratifiedKFold(10), scoring='neg_log_loss')
rfecv.fit(X2, target2)

rfecv1 = RFECV(estimator=rfc, step=1, cv=StratifiedKFold(10), scoring='neg_log_loss')
rfecv1.fit(X1, target1)

Model Selection¶

In [46]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=0).fit(Xred_train, yred_train)
pred_pred_test = clf.predict_proba(Xred_test)
pred_pred_train = clf.predict_proba(Xred_train)

clf.score(Xred_train,yred_train)
Out[46]:
0.890539483971853

$\mathcal{L} = - \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} y_i \log(p_i) + (1-y_i) \log(1-p_i)$

where yi is the true (but withheld) quality outcome for wine i in the test data set, and pi is the predicted probability of good quality for wine i . Larger values of $\mathcal{L}$ indicate poorer predictions. Your goal then is to minimize the "Log Loss".
